<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec_boundary" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Boundaries</title>
  
				<subsubsection>
	<title>Simulation Activity</title>
	
			  
			<activity>
				<title>String Boundary</title>
				<introduction>
		<p>
		</p>
		<p>Play with this <url href="https://phet.colorado.edu/sims/html/wave-on-a-string/latest/wave-on-a-string_en.html" visual="simulation"/> for a few minutes.</p>
	</introduction>
				<task>
					<statement>
						<p>Write an interesting observation you made using the simulation. Try to connect your observation to something you have experienced in your everyday life.</p>
					</statement>
				</task>
			  <task>
				<statement>
					<p>If you have not done so already, follow these steps in the simulation:</p>
				<p>
				<ul>
				<li>Click on the Pulse button and reduce the damping to zero.</li>
				<li>With the right end <em>fixed</em>, click on the green Pulse button once and observe what happens.</li>
				<li>Develop a rule for what happens to a wave pulse when it reflects from a fixed end.</li>
				<li>Click on the yellow Restart button.</li>
				<li>With the right end <em>loose</em>, click on the green Pulse button once and observe what happens.</li>
				<li>Develop a rule for what happens to a wave pulse when it reflects from a loose end.</li>
				</ul>
				</p>
				</statement>
			  <answer>
				
				<p>Reflections from fixed ends tend to flip over, while reflections from free ends do not.</p>
				
				<figure xml:id="hard">
    	<caption>
	A wave reflecting from a fixed end.
	</caption>
    	<image source="wave/hard.gif" width = "50%" ></image>
</figure>	

<figure xml:id="soft">
    	<caption>
	A wave reflecting from a free end.
	</caption>
    	<image source="wave/soft.gif" width = "50%" ></image>
</figure>	
				</answer>
			</task>
						
				</activity>
			
		</subsubsection>






